04303nam a22006255i 9780226506241DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017018769  a9780226506241  a(DE-B1597)550171  a(OCoLC)1012126181  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDS797.32.G836bM384 2017 4aDS797.32.G836bM384 2017 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.8009512/752231 aMathews, Gordon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe World in Guangzhou :bAfricans and Other Foreigners in South China’s Global Marketplace /cLinessa Dan Lin, Gordon Mathews, Yang Yang. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b21 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tONE. Introduction -- tTWO. Foreigners in Guangzhou -- tTHREE. African-Chinese Relations -- tFOUR. Low-End Globalization -- tFIVE. Legal-Illegal in Guangzhou -- tSIX. Logistics Agents, Middlemen, and Cultural Brokers -- tSEVEN. Religion in a Foreign World -- tEIGHT. Romance, Love, Marriage, and Families -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnly decades ago, the population of Guangzhou was almost wholly Chinese. Today, it is a truly global city, a place where people from around the world go to make new lives, find themselves, or further their careers. A large number of these migrants are small-scale traders from Africa who deal in Chinese goods—often knockoffs or copies of high-end branded items—to send back to their home countries. In The World in Guangzhou, Gordon Mathews explores the question of how the city became a center of “low-end globalization” and shows what we can learn from that experience about similar transformations elsewhere in the world. Through detailed ethnographic portraits, Mathews reveals a world of globalization based on informality, reputation, and trust rather than on formal contracts. How, he asks, can such informal relationships emerge between two groups—Chinese and sub-Saharan Africans—that don't share a common language, culture, or religion? And what happens when Africans move beyond their status as temporary residents and begin to put down roots and establish families? Full of unforgettable characters, The World in Guangzhou presents a compelling account of globalization at ground level and offers a look into the future of urban life as transnational connections continue to remake cities around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfricanszChinazGuangzhou. 0aAfricans-China-Guangzhou. 0aBusiness enterpriseszChinazGuangzhou. 0aBusiness enterprises-China-Guangzhou. 0aGuangzhou (China)-Ethnic relations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGuangzhou.  aforeigners.  alow-end globalization.  amulti-cultural China.  asub-Saharan African traders.1 aLin, Linessa Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aYang, Yang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226506241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226506241/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles